    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>For the last 36 years I have been one of ''the ones who can't see anymore,'' as the actor Gary Sinise describes wounded veterans in Bob Herbert's April 2 column (''Our National Debt''). With virtually no help from elected officials and most national veterans groups, it took me until 1998 to receive benefits for Vietnam war-related legal blindness.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>For the last 36 years I have been one of ''the ones who can't see anymore,'' as the actor Gary Sinise describes wounded veterans in Bob Herbert's April 2 column (''Our National Debt''). With virtually no help from elected officials and most national veterans groups, it took me until 1998 to receive benefits for Vietnam war-related legal blindness.</p>
        <p>If Mr. Sinise and the proposed Americans Disabled for Life Memorial might remind people that we could still use a hand (a ride to a park, getting to and selecting food at the grocery store, retrieving money from an ATM, even going to a movie), our lives would be less sterile.</p>
        <p>Perhaps the only good thing to come out of this war is the wider awareness that many wounds of war are endless.</p>
        <p>Bruce Rider  Grapevine, Tex., April 3, 2007</p>
      </block>
